		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> What shadow strategies are still viable in the Open format?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.59)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 5, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> What Shadow Strategies are still viable in the Open Format? <br />
<br />
The best way to begin to answer this question is to go back to basics. There are three ways to win the game. Let&#8217;s figure out the viability of different shadow tactics by going through the different ways to win:<br />
<br />
1. Kill the ring-bearer: Ahhhhh... a timeless classic. What viable shadow strategies can still accomplish this? Above and beyond all else, Moria. People were way too quick to dismiss Moria with the release of the Two Towers. I think the quote was, &#8220;Moria receives not one card in the Two Towers set.&#8221; Then, I answer, who else is Cavern Entrance supposed to help? The Uruks certainly don&#8217;t like it. Savageries and Ambitions become mute points. What about the Nazgul? Certainly a fellowship needs a few tricks up their sleeves to fend off RingWraiths? Perhaps, but Attea and Cantea (two of the most popular choices) aren&#8217;t big fans of the Cavern Entrance. The only way Frodo survives a Moria swarm is through a skirmish event or archery. We have now eliminated half the problem so all that&#8217;s left is the archery. Therefore a very viable shadow strategy would be a Moria swarm that can answer the archery problem. <br />
2. Corrupt the ring-bearer : This is the most challenging way to win. It will always require the right cards at the right time. Therefore card manipulation will be key. Can a shadow side accomplish this on their own? Not so much. They&#8217;ll need the help of dwarves. Therefore another viable shadow strategy (which is a new one, never seen before, most likely) would be a corruption by using a Raider/Sauron combo and aided by a dwarf-based fellowship in order to set up correctly. It won&#8217;t be easy to build but will be well worth it when you see the look on your opponents&#8217; faces. <br />
3. Get the ring-bearer to the end of the site path without having to carry him in a coffin : This used to be the way to go and was the easiest of the three ways to win. Nowadays, not so much. Shadow strategies seem very intent on killing Frodo, so much so that the Fellowship side is there to complement the Shadow side (by setting up great shadow hands and by single moving for maximum cycling). However, a good shadow strategy that could aid your fellowship in doing this would be through the use of Uruk Trackers. I don&#8217;t remember the last time I saw stopping power like these guys have. And as a special bonus, they have shadow conditions they can throw down on the companions and then with Grima, fill the free-peoples&#8217; player with their own cards. This is the first time that a shadow card has a direct positive effect on its Free Peoples&#8217; half of the deck. If the shadow player can manage to send 3 or 4 cards up into the hand, won&#8217;t they then be able to have a relatively easy double move? This won&#8217;t work as well against a Moria opponent because they can then ditch the cards with They Are Coming. But at what sacrifice? It seems to me that they won&#8217;t go and discard their Blade of Aragorn when they might see Ugluk next site. What about those Armors? Nah, they better hang on to them as well. So there is now a viable shadow strategy that aids your fellowship in getting to the end of the site path while not necessarily stopping your opponents&#8217; fellowship but rather setting up easy double moves.<br />
<br />
Those are what I see as being extremely viable shadow strategies in the new Open format. Now let&#8217;s sum up by going though a list of shadow strategies and noting which of the three aforementioned ways to win, each strategy is hoping for:<br />
&#61623; Dunland: This is certainly a viable shadow strategy. However, if a Dunland player wants to win, they have to take the archery threat seriously. Simply playing with 4 copies of Hides is not enough to win you a PT Cruiser. It will require more thought than that. Good luck. You should still go for a fellowship win, however. Dunland&#8217;s force is in stopping power (especially against Rohan decks).<br />
&#61623; Uruk Archers: Most definitely a viable shadow strategy. However, somewhat unstable. You must take into account large fellowships as well as hobbits that discard and come back fresh. Make sure you respond to these threats seriously if you want to attempt this deck. An Uruk Archery deck is going to win by killing the ring-bearer or possibly by corruption (but that&#8217;s only because he puts the ring on instead of getting arrow through his eye).<br />
&#61623; Uruk Bomb: Very stable. Very reliable. This is still certainly a viable deck strategy. You don&#8217;t really need to adapt this shadow strategy much. It can handle pretty much everything a fellowship throws at it. You might want, just the same, to throw in a couple of condition removers just in case Betrayal of Isengard or something equally annoying shows up. The Uruk Bomb player is going for a fellowship win. They&#8217;ll kill the ring-bearer only if he&#8217;s stupid. This deck has tremendous stopping power as well as infinite bluffing capability. I have stopped opponents with spending only four twilight of the pool. However, is the Keeper of Isengard going to get an erratum and thus change this deck&#8217;s potential? Who knows?<br />
&#61623; Isengard Orcs: Don&#8217;t laugh. On their own, they are certainly NOT a threat. And not a viable shadow option. HOWEVER certain of these little buggers can have an incredible (some might say broken) effect when coupled up with other cultures (say, Moria). Complimenting other cultures, the Isengard Orcs remain a viable option. Not on their own. An Isengard Orc player combined with another culture is trying to win the game by killing Frodo.<br />
&#61623; Site-Control : A viable deck option for Dunland, not for Uruks. It complements a Dunland strategy nicely. It does not contribute enough to the Uruk Bomb. All it does is foster instability to a perfectly capable culture before site-control came out. Tower block, however, I wouldn&#8217;t agree. Uruk Site-Control is quite lethal in Tower Block (that&#8217;s another article for another day...). A Site-Control player is trying to win the game with their fellowship.<br />
&#61623; Moria Swarm: Ironically, still the most viable shadow strategy for killing the Ring-Bearer. Not one Moria card in all of Two-Towers, just new sites and yet Moria remains a beast. A Moria Swarm player is trying (sometimes without much effort) to kill the ring-bearer. Nazgul and Isengard cultures blend nicely with Moria Swarm as well. In fact, a tri-culture deck based around Moria Swarm is entirely possible (and entirely broken, in my mind). A lot of players think that Moria is really good because Rohan can&#8217;t get bonuses from Moria&#8217;s low vitality&#8217;s. Try to remember that these Orcs aren&#8217;t after Eomer or his pals. Frodo is on the menu for these guys.<br />
&#61623; Moria Archers: No longer a viable shadow strategy. Brown Lands was the only thing keeping this deck type alive. It&#8217;s gone, and so are the archers. Besides, why wouldn&#8217;t you play with the more reliable Uruk Archers? Or perhaps why not combine them? A Moria Archery player is trying (quite desperately) to kill the ring-bearer (or possibly corrupt through wound addition).<br />
&#61623; Moria Power: Okay, now I can admit that a GOOD Moria strategy has come and gone. The loss of the Balrog has caused the loss of the Moria Power deck. Sure you can still throw in a Cave Troll but let&#8217;s face it, the Troll is playing second fiddle to The Flame of Udun. On his own, the Scourge of the Black-Pit stinks worse than the never-ending moisture forming on Gollum&#8217;s lower lip. A Moria Power player was going (most of the time) for a fellowship win. <br />
&#61623; Watcher in the Water : Watch me as I send him through my office shredder. This guy is the bane of my existence because I tried a deck based around him once and now my friends won&#8217;t let me live it down. I once saw a guy get out the Watcher with 8 tentacles at site 4. The fellowship double moved past it taking (count them) 2 wounds. Someone who is playing a Watcher in the Water deck is trying to win the game with their fellowship (and also should be shot). <br />
&#61623; Southron Archery : This is not a viable shadow option (for the moment). The Uruks are much better equipped to handle a prepared fellowship. The Southrons need to be lucky enough to stumble onto a couple hobbits all by themselves to win. A Southron player is going for a fellowship win.<br />
&#61623; Easterling Power: Some think that adding burdens to power up your boys in order to break apart a fellowship is the best use of the new Easterling  sub-culture. This is not a viable shadow strategy. Only because you&#8217;re much better off concentrating on a corruption win (see the next strategy). An Easterling Power player is going for a fellowship win.<br />
&#61623; Easterling Corruption: On their own they can&#8217;t do it. But paired up with another culture, they become a very viable (yet unstable) shadow strategy. They&#8217;ll need the help of the Free Peoples&#8217; deck to assist in setting up the cards. This will take a great deal of imagination and some great deck-building tactics but it is quite possible and lethal to the Ring-Bearer&#8217;s resistance. An Easterling Corruption player is trying to win the game by Corruption.<br />
&#61623; Nazgul Power: In my opinion (which many don&#8217;t share), this is no longer a viable deck strategy. The fellowship&#8217;s choke potential is too great, the condition removal is too great, and the annoyance of flaming brands playable on everyone is too great. I&#8217;m sorry but no site 3 Ford, then no early game ambush. The Nazgul Power player is trying to kill the ring-bearer or perhaps slow down the fellowship enough early on to get their own fellowship far ahead. <br />
&#61623; Nazgul Twilight: Not a viable shadow strategy. Same problems as the Power Nazgul. A Twilight Nazgul player is trying to kill the ring-bearer.<br />
&#61623; Ferny/Frost: This is still a viable shadow strategy. The problem is, in big event, people get wind of what you&#8217;re playing and adjust their play accordingly. This is a surprise deck that works best when it catches Frodo off his guard. A Ferny/Frost player is trying to win the game by killing the Ring-Bearer.<br />
&#61623; Sauron Power: Without the late-game swarm of Tol Brandir, they&#8217;re not what they used to be. This is no longer (and never has been ) a viable deck-strategy. Too much condition removal. A Sauron Power player is trying to win the game with his fellowship.<br />
&#61623; Sauron Corruption: Now we&#8217;re talking. What used to be a dead-strategy and laughed upon by many now has Easterling support for easy burden-addition. This is most certainly a viable deck-option and coupled with the right Free Peoples&#8217; side supporting the shadow, this could catch MANY people by surprise. No Sam early on either to slow down the burdens. Unfortunately, Ring-Bound Ranger decks will drive those Orcs BANANAS. A Sauron Corruption player is trying to win the game by Corrupting the Ring-Bearer.<br />
<br />
So that should just about cover everything. Please note that it may appear that I&#8217;ve been vague in places and kept you guessing. This is intentional. I&#8217;ve tried to avoid mentioning specific cards in the discussion because I&#8217;m not here to spoon-feed players. I find it much more exciting in discovering killer deck ideas on your own. <br />
<br />
Also note that these strategies are named off at a specific moment in time. I don&#8217;t want people this summer to wag this in my face saying how wrong I was about The Watcher in the Water because Battle of Helm&#8217;s Deep, for some reason, comes out with +6 war clubs playable on Tentacles. As of right now, this is what I see in terms of strategy and I am quite sure in two months, I&#8217;ll be seeing other things.<br />
<br />
Until then, I hope this has been informative and I look forward to seeing new free peoples&#8217; strategies that will respond to this growing threat of Shadow-Based decks. <br />
<br />
There will be no dawn for men. <br />
<br />
